The first track from the album to be made available was "[[Galang]]".  It was initially released in late 2003  by independent label Showbiz Records, which pressed and distributed 500 promotional copies.  This was before M.I.A. signed with XL Recordings.<ref name="Knox">{{cite web|url=http://www.thefader.com/articles/2006/01/06/ya-ya-heeeeeeey|title=Now Thing|work=[[The Fader]] |accessdate=8 February 2009|date=2004|first=Knox|last=Robinson}}</ref>  The song was re-released on XL as the second official single from the album in September 2004,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/cg/amg.dll?p=amg&sql=10:wifwxqysldhe|title=Galang (CD Single)
|work=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=8 February 2009}}</ref> and again in October 2005, under the title "Galang '05", with a remix by [[Serj Tankian]].<ref name="stylusmia2005">{{cite web |url=http://www.stylusmagazine.com/feature.php?ID=1941 |title=M.I.A. &ndash; Interview &ndash; Stylus Magazine| work = [[Stylus Magazine]] | date = 7 November 2005| dateformat=dmy|accessdate=18 December 2007}}</ref>  The first officially released single "[[Sunshowers]]", was M.I.A.'s first release on XL Recordings and was released on 5 July 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://allmusic.com/cg/amg.dll?p=amg&sql=10:aifwxqwrldse|title=Sunshowers
|work=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=10 February 2009|dateformat=dmy}}</ref>  It was supported by a music video directed by Indian film-maker [[Rajesh Touchriver]].<ref name="Knox" />  Following the re-release of "Galang", the third single from the album, "[[Bucky Done Gun]]", was released on 26 July 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://allmusic.com/cg/amg.dll?p=amg&sql=10:0nfoxqrsldfe|title=Bucky Done Gun
|work=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=10 February 2009|dateformat=dmy}}</ref>  The video was directed by [[Anthony Mandler]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/videos/mia/72817/bucky-done-gun.jhtml|title=M.I.A. - "Bucky Done Gun"
|publisher=[[MTV]] |accessdate=10 February 2009|dateformat=dmy}}</ref>

In December 2004, M.I.A. self-released a [[mixtape]] entitled ''[[Piracy Funds Terrorism]]'', produced by herself and Diplo, as a "teaser" for the album.  The release features rough mixes of tracks from ''Arular'' mashed up with songs by other artists, and was promoted by word-of-mouth.<ref name="cbcmia05" /><ref name="stylusmia2005" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.villagevoice.com/music/0451,wolk,59374,22.html |title=Booty Call|work=[[The Village Voice]]|date=14 December 2004|accessdate=11 February 2009|dateformat=dmy|first=Douglas|last=Wolk}}</ref>  In early 2005, after the release of ''Arular'', an extensive collection of fan-made remixes of M.I.A.'s work was uploaded, expanded and made available as an "online mixtape" on XL's official website, under the banner ''Online Piracy Funds Terrorism''.<ref name="stylusmia2005"/>  M.I.A. toured extensively during 2005 to promote the album.  The [[Arular Tour]] included concerts in North America supporting [[LCD Soundsystem]] and appearances at music festivals in Europe, Japan and South America.<ref name="05tourmia">{{cite web | last=Chekuru|first= Kavitha| title= M.I.A. Announces Headlining Tour| url= http://www.pitchforkmedia.com/article/news/34916-mia-announces-headlining-tour| work = [[Pitchfork Media]] | date=25 July 2005 | accessdate=11 February 2009|dateformat=dmy}}</ref><ref name="05tourmia2">{{cite web | last=Martin|first= Megan| title= LCD Soundsystem, M.I.A. Kick Off Tour Tonight!| url= http://www.pitchforkmedia.com/article/news/34604-lcd-soundsystem-mia-kick-off-tour-tonight| work = [[Pitchfork Media]] | date=10 May 2005 | accessdate=11 February 2009|dateformat=dmy}}</ref>  In November 2005 she supported [[Gwen Stefani]] at a number of dates on here [[Harajuku Lovers Tour 2005|Harajuku Lovers Tour]].<ref name="05tourmia3">{{cite web | last=Llewellyn|first= Kati| url= http://www.pitchforkmedia.com/article/news/35282-mia-to-open-for-gwen-stefani|title=M.I.A. to Open for Gwen Stefani| work = [[Pitchfork Media]] | date=13 October 2005 | accessdate=11 February 2009|dateformat=dmy}}</ref>

''Arular'' was nominated for the [[Mercury Prize]] in the UK,<ref name="best5">{{cite web | url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/4217140.stm|title=Antony and Johnsons win Mercury| work = [[BBC News]]|publisher=[[BBC|British Broadcasting Corporation]] | date=7 September 2005 | accessdate=11 February 2009|dateformat=dmy}}</ref> and was named as the best album of the year by ''[[Stylus Magazine|Stylus]]'',<ref name="best1">{{cite web | url= http://www.stylusmagazine.com/feature.php?ID=2045|title=Stylus Magazine's Top 50 Albums of 2005| work = [[Stylus Magazine|Stylus]] | date=19 December 2005 | author=Stylus Staff|accessdate=11 February 2009|dateformat=dmy}}</ref> and was number two on ''[[The Village Voice]]'''s 33rd annual ''[[Pazz & Jop]]'' poll for the Best Album of 2005.<ref name="vvmia05">{{cite web  | title= The 33rd Annual Village Voice pazz&jop critics<U+2019> poll | work=[[The Village Voice]] | url= http://www.villagevoice.com/pazzandjop05/winners.php?type=album | date=31 December 2005 | dateformat=dmy | accessdate=21 December 2007}}</ref>  The [[Washington City Paper]] also chose it as the second best album of the year,<ref name="best4">{{cite web | url= http://www.washingtoncitypaper.com/special/2005top20.html|title=The CP 2005 Top 20|work=[[Washington City Paper]]| publisher = [[Creative Loafing|Creative Loafing Inc.]] | date=30 December 2005 &ndash; 5 January 2006 |accessdate=11 February 2009|dateformat=dmy}}</ref> and both [[Pitchfork Media]] and ''[[Slant Magazine]]'' named ''Arular'' the number 4 best album of 2005.<ref name="best2">{{cite web | url= http://www.pitchforkmedia.com/article/feature/38517-staff-list-top-50-albums-of-2005/page_5|title=Top 50 Albums of 2005| publisher = [[Pitchfork Media]] | date=31 December 2005 | author=Pitchfork Staff|accessdate=11 February 2009|dateformat=dmy}}</ref><ref name="best3">{{cite web | url= http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/features/2005yearinmusic.asp|title=2005 : Year in Rewind| publisher = [[Slant Magazine]] | date= 2005 | first=Sal|last=Cinquemani|accessdate=11 February 2009|dateformat=dmy}}</ref> and it was listed as one of the year's five best albums by ''[[The Guardian]]''.<ref name="Empire" />  ''Arular'' was featured in the book ''[[1001 Albums You Must Hear Before You Die]]'', where it was described as "the most sparkling debut since [[Madonna (Madonna album)|Madonna's first album]]".<ref>{{cite book|title=1001 Albums You Must Hear Before You Die|first=Robert|last=Dimery|pages=947|isbn=1-8440-3392-9|year=2005|publisher=Cassell Illustrated}}</ref>  [[Thom Yorke]] of [[alternative rock]] band [[Radiohead]] cited M.I.A.'s "complete block and chop repeat, chop repeat, chop, not finished" method of music making on ''Arular'' as an influence on his own work, saying that it reminded him "of that thing of just picking up a [[guitar]] and the first three [[chords]] you write and being like, yep, that's good. Stop. End" as opposed to "agonizing over the [[hi-hat]] sound which seems to happen with [[Programming (music)|programming]] and [[electronica]] a lot of the time. You can feel the pain going on."<ref name="Rs08">
{{cite web| title=Radiohead's Secret Influences, from Fleetwood Mac to Thomas Pynchon| date=24 January 2008| work=[[Rolling Stone]] | url =http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/18060334/radioheads_secret_influences_from_fleetwood_mac_to_thomas_pynchon| dateformat=dmy|accessdate = 28 September 2008}}</ref>

===Critical reception===
''Arular'' was released to widespread critical acclaim, scoring 88 on [[Metacritic]].<ref name="Metacritic Arular">{{cite web | title= M.I.A.: Arular (2005): Reviews | work= [[MetaCritic]] | url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/artists/mia/arular | date= 31 December 2005 | dateformat=mdy| accessdate=23 December 2007}}</ref>  ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' appreciated its fusion of "[[hip hop]]'s cockiness with [[dancehall]]'s shimmy and the cheap and noisy aesthetics of [[punk rock|punk]]" and claimed that ''Arular'' would be regarded as the best political album of the year.<ref name="Metacritic Arular"/><ref>{{cite article |author=| title= Reviews| url= | work = [[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|publisher=Spin Media LLC| date=March 2005 | page=88}}</ref>  Adam Webb, writing for [[Yahoo! Music]] described the album's style as "professionally amateurish", but said that "[M.I.A.'s] scattergun approach effortlessly appropriates the music of various different cultures and filters them through the most elementary equipment.  Dancehall is the primary influence, but also one of many seismic collisions with several other genres....with the results of such displacement and politicisation writ large all over" the album.<ref name="yahoomia05">{{cite web | last=Webb|first=Adam | title= MIA &ndash; Arular 2005| url=http://uk.launch.yahoo.com/050426/33/1xkwz.html | work = [[Yahoo! Music]] | date=26 April 2005| dateformat=dmy|accessdate=6 October 2008}}</ref>  In his review for ''[[Stylus Magazine]]'', Josh Timmermann described ''Arular'' as "a swaggering, spitting, utterly contemporary album" and went on to say "We've not heard its like before".<ref name="stylusmiaarularreview"/> ''[[Rolling Stone (magazine)|Rolling Stone]]'' found ''Arular'' "weird, playful, unclassifiable, sexy, brilliantly addictive".<ref> {{cite web | url= http://www.rollingstone.com/reviews/album/6857856/arular | title = Arular : M.I.A. : Review : Rolling Stone | dateformat=dmy |accessdate= 23 December 2007 | work= [[Rolling Stone]]}} </ref> ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' said "All the elements are deftly held together by the MC/songstress' ability to make each track her own".<ref name="Metacritic Arular"/>  [[Sasha Frere-Jones]], writing in ''[[The New Yorker]]'', described the album as "genuine [[world music]]", based on "the weaving of the political into the fabric of what are still, basically, [[dance music|dance tunes]]".<ref name="mianeyyorkernov04">{{cite web | last= Frere Jones|first=Sasha | title= Bingo in Swansea: Maya Arulpragsam<U+2019>s world| work= [[The New Yorker]] | url= http://www.newyorker.com/archive/2004/11/22/041122crmu_music| date= 22 November 2004 | dateformat=dmy | accessdate=24 May 2008}}</ref>  Other reviewers were not as complimentary, however.  ''[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]'' stated that the album, although strong, was not as "mindblowing" as many critics were making out.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2005/08/mia-arular.html|title=M.I.A. &ndash; Arular|first=Jeff|last=Leven|work=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]|publisher=Paste Media Group LLC|date=16 August 2005|dateformat=dmy|accessdate=27 January 2009}}</ref>  ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]'' characterised the album as "style mag-cool pop-rap" and stated that it lacked the substance suggested by M.I.A.'s decision to name it after her father.<ref>{{cite article |author=| title=Q Reviews| url= | work = [[Q (magazine)|Q]]|publisher=[[Bauer Media Group]]| date=May 2005 | page=105}}</ref>

===Commercial performance===
By mid-2007, the album had sold 129,000 copies in the United States.<ref>{{cite web | last=Cohen|first=Jonathan| title= M.I.A. Dropping Second Album In August| url= http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/news/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1003571180 | work = [[Billboard magazine|Billboard]] | year=2007 | dateformat=dmy|accessdate= 21 June 2007}}</ref>  It only reached number 190 on the [[Billboard 200]] albums chart, but made it to number 3 on the [[Top Electronic Albums]] chart, and reached the top 20 on two of the magazine's other component charts.<ref name="Amgmiach" />  In the UK it climbed only to number 98 on the main [[UK Albums Chart]],<ref name="Zob" /> but did reach the top 10 of the Indie Albums Chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4158/is_20050429/ai_n14605240|title=The Charts: Music|work=The Independent|dateformat=dmy|accessdate=29 January 2009|date=29 April 2005}}</ref>  The album also charted in several countries in mainland [[Europe]].<ref name="swedishcharts">{{cite web|url=http://swedishcharts.com/showitem.asp?key=17937&cat=a|title=M.I.A. &ndash; Arular (Album)|publisher=SwedishCharts.com|dateformat=dmy|accessdate=11 December 2008}}</ref>

